                     <p>
                        <seg type="docType">Judgement.</seg>
                        <placeName key="place_116089">Wigan (Lancashire)</placeName>. <origDate notBefore="1323" notAfter="1324">17 Ed. II (1324). </origDate>. Judgement (from the Plea Rolls of 17 Ed. II) against Robert de Cliderhou, parson of Wigan, who had supplied Thomas, earl of Lancaster, with two men at arms (one being his own son Adam) and four foot soldiers well armed, against the king and of preaching publicly in his church on behalf of the earl. He is found guilty, is bailed in 1000 marks by thirteen persons and at last fined (but the amount of the fine is lost) (copy, in the reign of Ed. III).</p>
